\description{
\code{build_fishbase_sealifebase_ecology_db()} reads local FishBase and
SeaLifeBase parquet exports, reconstructs native FishBase/SeaLifeBase
taxonomy locally, cleans species and ecology tables separately by source,
collapses ecology flags into compact metadata columns, joins by \code{source} and
\code{spec_code}, and returns species-level and higher-rank ecology evidence
tables. Species-level rows are uniquely identified by \code{source + spec_code}.

This function does not use \code{rfishbase} and does not make live API calls. If
parquet files are missing and \code{download_if_missing = TRUE}, it downloads the
current Source Cooperative parquet files with \code{curl::curl_download()}.

FishBase/SeaLifeBase native taxonomy is used rather than NCBI taxonomy.
FishBase kingdom/phylum are inferred as \code{Metazoa}/\code{Chordata} because the
native FishBase taxonomy tables are fish-focused and do not carry those ranks
explicitly. Only standard ranks (\code{kingdom}, \code{phylum}, \code{class}, \code{order},
\code{family}, \code{genus}, and \code{species}) are emitted as \code{taxon_rank} rows.

Environment evidence is represented in a WoRMS-like collapsed form such as
\code{"marine; brackish; freshwater"}. \code{ecology_habitat_broad} is derived only
from the species-table \code{DemersPelag} field. Ecology-table flags are retained
as compact metadata columns such as \code{ecology_zone},
\code{ecology_water_column_zone}, \code{ecology_mobility}, \code{ecology_size_class},
\code{ecology_substrate}, and \code{ecology_special_habitat}, but they do not determine
\code{ecology_habitat_broad}.

\code{depth_min} and \code{depth_max} come from the full reported depth range;
\code{common_depth_min} and \code{common_depth_max} come from the common depth range
when available. \code{ecology_depth_zone} is based on \code{depth_max}, not
\code{common_depth_max}, because it is intended to capture possible deep
occurrence rather than common occurrence.

Aggregated semicolon-separated ecology terms are split, trimmed, and
de-duplicated before being returned. Dominant ecology fields such as
\code{dominant_environment}, \code{dominant_habitat_broad}, and
\code{dominant_depth_zone} contain one deterministic value only, with the paired
\verb{*_prop} column giving the dominant term count divided by all usable split
terms.

Higher-rank rows are aggregated from species-level ecology evidence, while
native rank-table metadata is retained in fields such as \code{common_name},
\code{rank_water_salinity}, \code{rank_habitat_note}, \code{rank_distribution}, and
\code{rank_etymology}.
\code{rank_habitat_note} is native rank-table text metadata and should not be
confused with aggregated \code{ecology_habitat_broad}. For higher-rank rows,
\code{ecology_evidence_strength} summarises support for the dominant broad habitat:
\code{high} means at least 10 species with habitat evidence and a dominant
proportion of at least 0.8; \code{moderate} means at least 5 species and a
dominant proportion of at least 0.6; \code{mixed} means multiple broad habitats
with no moderate/high dominance; \code{low} means fewer than 5 species with some
habitat evidence; and \code{unknown} means no useful species-level broad habitat
